<TITLE> Djokovic beats Kubot to win Serbia Open </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BELGRADE, May 11 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - World number three Novak Djokovic triumphed on home soil when he beat Poland's Lukasz Kubot 6-3 7-6 to win the inaugural Serbia Open on Sunday. After losing three consecutive finals in Miami, Monte Carlo and Rome, top seed Djokovic delighted the 7,900 capacity home crowd to lift the 13th singles title of his career in an event organised and co-sponsored by his family. He put on a shirt saying "Serbia, I love you" and hugged his parents and brothers in their courtside box after overpowering the unseeded Kubot, who reached the final after he was readmitted into the tournament as a 'lucky loser'. Djokovic's outpour of joy contrasted with scenes from Saturday's semi-final win against Italian Andreas Seppi, when he asked his vociferously supportive father to leave after dropping the first set. "I wish to congratulate Kubot on the biggest success of his career and thank everyone who made this tournament happen," the 21-year-old Serb said after lifting the trophy. "I am also overjoyed to have won the tournament, it's not the biggest event I have ever won but I cherish it more than any other because it was in my hometown." Djokovic wrapped up the first set on a warm afternoon after racing to a 5-1 lead and then came from 5-2 down in the second to win the tiebreak without dropping a point. Kubot appeared close to forcing a third set but Djokovic produced his best shots when he needed to and his baseline power proved too much for the Pole. It was the end of a remarkable run for Kubot, who had lost his final qualifier to Slovakia's Dominik Hrbaty but rejoined the tournament after Belgium's Steve Darcis pulled out with a shoulder injury. For Djokovic, it was merely a warm-up for the upcoming Madrid Open and the French Open as he was rarely tested against unheralded riv
